      "question": "If $\\sin \\theta = \\frac{5}{13}$ and $\\theta$ is an acute angle, then the value of $\\frac{\\tan \\theta + \\sec \\theta}{\\cos \\theta}$ is equal to:",
      "answer": "(A)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Given $\\sin \\theta = \\frac{5}{13}$. In a right-angled triangle, $\\sin \\theta = \\frac{\\text{Opposite}}{\\text{Hypotenuse}} = \\frac{5}{13}$.",
          "Using the Pythagorean theorem, find the adjacent side: $\\text{Adjacent}^2 = 13^2 - 5^2 = 169 - 25 = 144$. So, $\\text{Adjacent} = 12$.",
          "Calculate the required ratios: $\\tan \\theta = \\frac{5}{12}$, $\\sec \\theta = \\frac{13}{12}$, and $\\cos \\theta = \\frac{12}{13}$.",
          "Substitute the values into the expression: $\\frac{\\frac{5}{12} + \\frac{13}{12}}{\\frac{12}{13}} = \\frac{\\frac{18}{12}}{\\frac{12}{13}} = \\frac{3}{2} \\times \\frac{13}{12} = \\frac{39}{24} = \\frac{13}{8}$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$\\sin \\theta = \\frac{5}{13} \\Rightarrow \\text{Opposite} = 5k, \\text{Hypotenuse} = 13k \\\\ \\text{Adjacent} = \\sqrt{(13k)^2 - (5k)^2} = \\sqrt{169k^2 - 25k^2} = 12k \\\\ \\tan \\theta = \\frac{5}{12}, \\sec \\theta = \\frac{13}{12}, \\cos \\theta = \\frac{12}{13} \\\\ \\frac{\\tan \\theta + \\sec \\theta}{\\cos \\theta} = \\frac{\\frac{5}{12} + \\frac{13}{12}}{\\frac{12}{13}} = \\frac{\\frac{18}{12}}{\\frac{12}{13}} = \\frac{3}{2} \\times \\frac{13}{12} = \\frac{39}{24} = \\frac{13}{8}$"
      },
